result.name: Bugfix release
Performance improvement release
result.description:
This release further reduces SlipCover's branch+line coverage overhead on Python 3.12 and later.
Thanks to Mark Shannon and Ned Batchelder for comments/suggestions.

result.name: Minor maintenance release
result.description: This release moves the [manylinux](https://github.com/pypa/manylinux) based builds to 2.28, based on CentOS 8, as the previous image is reaching its end of life.

result.name: Fixes wheels for MacOS >14.2
result.description:
This release fixes certain SlipCover wheels on MacOS > 14.2 that caused errors like
```
dlopen(/opt/homebrew/lib/python3.11/site-packages/slipcover/probe.abi3.so, 0x0002): bad bind opcode 0x00
```

result.name: Bug fix release
result.description: This release fixes an issue leading to `ValueError: line ..., column ...-... is not a valid range` exceptions on Python 3.12+ while using SlipCover.

result.name: Reissue of v1.0.9
result.description: This release simply re-issues v1.0.9: GitHub lacks Python 3.8 for `macos-latest`, causing the build and upload workflow to partially fail.

result.name: Bugfix release
result.description:
This release fixes a bug instrumenting certain bytecodes on Python 3.11.
Thanks to @LilyFoote for the bug report (including narrowing the problem down).

result.name: Reissue for Python 3.13 capable PyPI wheels
result.description: This release fixes none of the wheels on PyPI tagged as appropriate for Python 3.13.

result.name: Python 3.13 support, small improvements
Improved subprocess performance, bug fixes
Added option to merge coverage files
result.description:
This release adds `--merge`, which merges JSON coverage files, as in:

```
slipcover --merge a.json b.json --out c.json
```

Closes #12.

result.name: `pytest-forked` support, improved file matching
Improves JSON output / Codecov compatibility, adds workaround for rare issue
Adds scanning for sources never executed, fixes branch destination bugs
Added Python 3.12 support
Bug fix
result.description: This release fixes a bug which apparently only affects Python 3.10 when using branch coverage.

result.name: Bug fixes, improved fuzzing support
Simplified import interface, improved support for fuzzing
result.description:
This version makes no visible changes to Slipcover when used as a coverage analyzer.
It starts to improve Slipcover's `import` interface, making it easier to use for coverage-guided fuzzing.

result.name: New options, bugfix
Python 3.11 wheels, experimental option, source distribution fixes
Bugfix release
Branch coverage support, per-file and global summaries
result.description:
This release:
- adds branch coverage measuring support to slipcover; simply run it with `--branch` to get it.
- adds a "meta" item identify the source of the coverage information, as well as per-file and global summaries to the JSON output (issue #2).

result.name: Packaging tweak
Python 3.11 support
Fixing file filtering
Fixes missing Apple Silicon (M1) code in wheels
result.description: An error in the build scripts was causing non-x86_64 code to be dropped.

result.name: Fixed pytest plugins not being loaded
Bugfix release: tracker loading on Windows
Fixing pytest import issue from v0.1.1
result.description: This release fixes https://github.com/plasma-umass/slipcover/issues/4 from v0.1.1, which happens with pytest isn't installed.

result.name: Improved pytest support

result.value:
SlipCover is available from [PyPI](https://pypi.org/project/slipcover).
You can install it like any other Python module with
```console
pip3 install slipcover
```

You could then run your Python script with:
```console
python3 -m slipcover myscript.py
```
parent_header: SlipCover: Near Zero-Overhead Python Code Coverage

result.value:
SlipCover can also execute a Python module, as in:
```console
python3 -m slipcover -m pytest -x -v
```
which starts `pytest`, passing it any options (`-x -v` in this example)
after the module name.
No plug-in is required for pytest.
result.original_header: Using it with a test harness
parent_header: SlipCover: Near Zero-Overhead Python Code Coverage
